{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1784492958,"nonce":"vxR6ETw2VJ9T6Nj2tNARrd1fRQ0=","title":"PG exclusion constraints: same-name-swap variants, operator/opclass fidelity, INCLUDE, column co-operation ordering","message":"Follow-up to acb1c6d Phase 3 PR 5 (PostgreSQL exclusion constraints, merged a7d72a7 / PR #115). PR 5 fully delivers the scalar-and-range, squealy-authored exclusion contract (multi-element WITH operators, operator classes, partial WHERE, DEFERRABLE, sort direction/null order; publish then introspect then replan-empty, live-tested on PG with btree_gist). These edges were deferred with maintainer sign-off; none is silent corruption in that contract.\n\nSAME-NAME SWAP ORDERING (the bounded index-backed variant IS handled: an exclusion vs a same-name index/UNIQUE/PK is rejected at plan time via ObjectKind::Exclusion). Still open:\n1. An exclusion foo replaced by a same-name CHECK or FOREIGN KEY on the same table mis-orders: the add runs before the DropExclusion, and PostgreSQL rejects the duplicate constraint name (constraint names are unique per table). This is a pre-existing unhandled class for ALL constraint kinds, not just exclusions.\n2. An exclusion moved between tables while keeping its name mis-orders: both models claim the same schema-wide relation name, so table-name ordering emits the new table's add before the old table's drop and PostgreSQL rejects the still-owned index name. Niche refactor; loud at apply.\n\nOPERATOR / OPERATOR-CLASS FIDELITY:\n3. A schema-qualified custom operator (for example an operator in an extension outside search_path) introspects as the bare oprname, dropping the namespace, so an authored qualified spelling churns. Same class as the domain-over-user-defined-base qualification edge.\n4. An exclusion element that explicitly names its method default operator class (for example gist_int4_ops) churns forever: introspection drops default operator classes to empty while the desired keeps the name. Unusual authoring (omitting it is the norm and round-trips); mirrors existing latent index behavior.\n\nMODELING GAP:\n5. A covering INCLUDE column on an exclusion is correctly ignored during introspection (no fabricated element) but is not modeled, so it is silently dropped.\n\nCOLUMN CO-OPERATION ORDERING (flagged by the PR review bot; VERIFIED pre-existing and shared with the existing index/check/FK handling, not exclusion regressions):\n6. Dropping a column that a single-column exclusion (or index) uses auto-drops the dependent object during ALTER TABLE DROP COLUMN, so the plan's later DROP CONSTRAINT (or DROP INDEX) fails with does-not-exist. Verified live: a single-column index behaves identically. squealy emits column drops before dependent-object drops and neither uses IF EXISTS.\n7. Renaming a column referenced by a dependent exclusion (or index) emits a spurious AlterExclusion (or AlterIndex) drop-and-recreate, because apply_column_rename rewrites only the column add/drop into a RenameColumn and does not suppress dependent-object diffs; PostgreSQL auto-updates the constraint/index on RENAME COLUMN.\n\nItems 6 and 7 are cross-cutting (order dependent-object drops before column drops / suppress a cascaded drop / suppress a rename-covered alter) and belong in a dedicated change spanning indexes, checks, foreign keys, and exclusions, not an object-add PR. Common thread across all: none is silent corruption in the scalar/range squealy-authored replan-empty contract; failure modes are a rejected/aborted plan (loud), churn under unusual authoring, or an external-DB fidelity gap.","files":null}]}